{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01AmMi3GeEKAgb2HPrnNGvun","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Here is a complete summary of findings.\n\n---\n\n## Findings: Remote File Sources in MachineConfig and HTTP/HTTPS Validation\n\n### 1. MachineConfig YAML and Go Struct Examples with Remote Sources\n\nThere are no production MachineConfig YAML manifests in this repo that place an `http://` or `https://` URL directly in a `contents.source` field. All production and documentation examples use the `data:` URL scheme (inline, percent-encoded content).\n\n**What does appear in files:**\n\n- `/home/jsuri/random-testing/prashanth-help/machine-config-operator/pkg/server/testdata/machine-configs/test-config.yaml` (line 17) - uses a `data:,` URL with percent-encoded content:\n  ```yaml\n  contents:\n    source: \"data:,GROUP%3Dstable%0ASERVER%3Dhttp%3A%2F%2Flocalhost%3A32003%2Fv1%2Fupdate%0A\"\n  ```\n  The embedded content happens to reference an HTTP server, but the `source` field itself is a data URL.\n\n- `/home/jsuri/random-testing/prashanth-help/machine-config-operator/docs/MachineConfig.md` and `MachineConfigServer.md` - all `source` fields in examples use `data:` URLs exclusively.\n\n**Test code using HTTPS in `source` (ignition config merge references, not file contents):**\n\n- `/home/jsuri/random-testing/prashanth-help/machine-config-operator/pkg/controller/certrotation/helpers_test.go` (line 24) and `/home/jsuri/random-testing/prashanth-help/machine-config-operator/test/e2e-2of2/msbic_test.go` (line 189) - these embed ignition configs in `userData` secrets that have an HTTPS source in `ignition.config.merge[0].source` (the MCS endpoint `https://test-cluster-api:22623/config/worker`), which is the ignition bootstrap URL, not a file `contents.source`.\n\n- `/home/jsuri/random-testing/prashanth-help/machine-config-operator/test/extended-priv/util.go` (lines 789, 791) - the `getFileConfig` helper formats a JSON string `{\"contents\": {\"source\": \"%s\"}, ...}`, where the source is always passed in as a base64 data URL via `GetBase64EncodedFileSourceContent`.\n\n### 2. The `Resource` Go Struct (Ignition File Source)\n\nThe vendored Ignition library defines the struct used in MachineConfig file specs:\n\n**`/home/jsuri/random-testing/prashanth-help/machine-config-operator/vendor/github.com/coreos/ignition/v2/config/v3_4/types/schema.go` (lines 207-212):**\n```go\ntype Resource struct {\n    Compression  *string      `json:\"compression,omitempty\"`\n    HTTPHeaders  HTTPHeaders  `json:\"httpHeaders,omitempty\"`\n    Source       *string      `json:\"source,omitempty\"`\n    Verification Verification `json:\"verification,omitempty\"`\n}\n```\n`FileEmbedded1.Contents` is of type `Resource`. This struct is the Go equivalent of the YAML `contents:` block under each file entry.\n\n### 3. URL Validation Logic: Which Schemes Are Accepted\n\nThe Ignition URL validation is the authoritative gate. It lives in the vendored Ignition library, and MCO calls it via `ValidateIgnition` -> `validate3.ValidateWithContext`.\n\n**`/home/jsuri/random-testing/prashanth-help/machine-config-operator/vendor/github.com/coreos/ignition/v2/config/v3_4/types/url.go` (the version used for Ignition 3.4):**\n```go\nfunc validateURL(s string) error {\n    u, err := url.Parse(s)\n    ...\n    switch u.Scheme {\n    case \"http\", \"https\", \"tftp\", \"gs\":\n        return nil\n    case \"s3\": ...\n    case \"arn\": ...\n    case \"data\": ...\n    default:\n        return errors.ErrInvalidScheme\n    }\n}\n```\n\nBoth `http://` and `https://` are accepted by Ignition validation. There is **no MCO-level enforcement that requires HTTPS**; both schemes pass validation.\n\nScheme support by Ignition version in the vendor tree:\n- v3.0, v3.1: `http`, `https`, `tftp`, `s3`, `data`\n- v3.2, v3.3, v3.4, v3.5: adds `gs` (Google Cloud Storage), `arn` (S3 ARN)\n\n**`HTTPHeaders` scheme restriction** (`/home/jsuri/random-testing/prashanth-help/machine-config-operator/vendor/github.com/coreos/ignition/v2/config/v3_4/types/resource.go`, lines 60-79): If `httpHeaders` are specified, the source URL must be `http` or `https`; other schemes (like `data:`) will fail with `ErrUnsupportedSchemeForHTTPHeaders`.\n\n### 4. MCO's Own Validation Does Not Add HTTP Restrictions\n\n**`/home/jsuri/random-testing/prashanth-help/machine-config-operator/pkg/controller/common/helpers.go`:**\n\n- `ValidateIgnition` (line 353): Delegates entirely to `validate3.ValidateWithContext` (or v2 equivalent), then checks file modes. No HTTP vs HTTPS check.\n- `ValidateMachineConfig` (line 447): Calls `ValidateIgnition`. No URL scheme restriction added.\n- `DecodeIgnitionFileContents` (line 403): Explicitly notes \"This function does not handle remote resources; it assumes they have already been fetched.\" It calls `dataurl.DecodeString` and will fail if passed a non-data URL.\n\n### 5. MCO's Policy on Remote Sources (Design Intent)\n\n**`/home/jsuri/random-testing/prashanth-help/machine-config-operator/docs/MachineConfig.md` (lines 9, 24, 36-38):**\n\nThe design explicitly states:\n> \"The MachineConfig served to the machines should be static and there should be no links to remote locations for dynamic configuration. This includes both remote sources for Ignition and remote files.\"\n> \"No remote sources in rendered MachineConfig: To ensure all the machines see the same configurations, remote sources need to be resolved to a snapshot at generation time.\"\n\nIn practice, the `writeFiles` function in the daemon (`/home/jsuri/random-testing/prashanth-help/machine-config-operator/pkg/daemon/update.go`, line 2477) has a comment: \"it doesn't fetch remote files and expects a flattened config file.\" The rendered MachineConfig is expected to have all `source` fields resolved to `data:` URLs before the daemon acts on them.\n\n### 6. The `once-from` Mode Does Accept HTTP/HTTPS\n\nThe daemon's `--once-from` flag (used for bootstrapping, not for cluster-managed configs) does allow HTTP/HTTPS:\n\n**`/home/jsuri/random-testing/prashanth-help/machine-config-operator/pkg/daemon/daemon.go` (lines 2838-2850):**\n```go\nif strings.HasPrefix(onceFrom, \"http://\") || strings.HasPrefix(onceFrom, \"https://\") {\n    contentFrom = onceFromRemoteConfig\n    resp, err := http.Get(onceFrom)\n    ...\n}\n```\nThis is for the bootstrap/onceFrom flow only, where a MachineConfig or Ignition config is fetched from a URL. Both `http://` and `https://` are accepted without any preference for one over the other.\n\n### Summary\n\n- There are no MachineConfig YAML examples with `http://` or `https://` in `contents.source` in the main codebase (only `data:` URLs appear in production code and documentation).\n- The Ignition-level schema (`Resource` struct) supports both schemes for `source`.\n- Ignition validation (`validateURL`) accepts both `http` and `https` (plus `tftp`, `gs`, `s3`, `arn`, `data`); there is no HTTPS-required rule.\n- MCO adds no additional HTTP-vs-HTTPS validation beyond what Ignition provides.\n- The MCO design explicitly discourages remote sources in rendered configs: any `http://` or `https://` `source` in a user-supplied MachineConfig should be resolved/fetched and replaced with an inline `data:` URL at render time.\n- The `once-from` mode in the daemon accepts both `http://` and `https://` URLs for the config file itself (not for file `contents.source`)."}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"97616e95-6991-412d-aaaf-43b45e95d486","uuid":"6c15f3b5-372c-4a89-879d-cee6c4fe1a64","timestamp":"2026-06-22T21:34:52.279Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"In the machine-config-operator repo at /home/jsuri/random-testing/prashanth-help/machine-config-operator, find examples of MachineConfig YAML or Go structs that use remote file sources (HTTP/HTTPS URLs in `contents.source` fields). Also look for any validation logic or documentation around HTTP vs HTTPS URLs for 