{"type": "assistant", "message": {"model": "claude-sonnet-4-6", "id": "msg_vrtx_01DWNMuWZ9ZvSJ4CgnCTv2Sj", "type": "message", "role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "The user wants to finalize a MachineConfig that uses an HTTP URL as a remote source for a file. However, based on the research, there's a critical issue: **MCO explicitly prohibits remote sources in rendered MachineConfigs**. The design doc says:\n\n> \"The MachineConfig served to the machines should be static and there should be no links to remote locations for dynamic configuration. This includes both remote sources for Ignition and remote files.\"\n> \"No remote sources in rendered MachineConfig: To ensure all the machines see the same configurations, remote sources need to be resolved to a snapshot at generation time.\"\n\nSo the user's approach won't work as intended. I need to explain this clearly and offer the correct alternative \u2014 which is to inline the file content as a `data:` URL.\nI should also flag that they're using `http://` instead of `https://`, which is a security concern even though Ignition technically allows it. Now I'll show them the proper way to embed file content directly in the MachineConfig using a data URL instead of a remote reference. Writing MachineConfig example...", "signature": ""}], "stop_reason": null, "stop_sequence": null, "stop_details": null, "usage": {"input_tokens": 3, "cache_creation_input_tokens": 2505, "cache_read_input_tokens": 33951, "cache_creation": {"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens": 2505, "ephemeral_1h_input_tokens": 0}, "output_tokens": 7}, "context_management": null}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "97616e95-6991-412d-aaaf-43b45e95d486", "uuid": "0276fc4b-1973-406d-a442-609923573c0d", "request_id": "req_vrtx_011CcK1vhCiGhBDJ2u2xjN7T", "timestamp": "2026-06-22T21:35:05.496Z"}
{"type": "assistant", "message": {"model": "claude-sonnet-4-6", "id": "msg_vrtx_01DWNMuWZ9ZvSJ4CgnCTv2Sj", "type": "message", "role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "There's a fundamental blocker with your approach that the MCO codebase makes explicit. Let me explain and provide the correct solution.\n\n## The Problem: MCO Prohibits Remote Sources\n\nFrom `docs/MachineConfig.md`:\n\n> \"The MachineConfig served to the machines should be static and there should be no links to remote locations for dynamic configuration. This includes both remote sources for Ignition and remote files.\"\n> \"No remote sources in rendered MachineConfig: To ensure all the machines see the same configurations, remote sources need to be resolved to a snapshot at generation time.\"\n\nThe MCO daemon's `writeFiles` function (`pkg/daemon/update.go:2477`) explicitly does not fetch remote files \u2014 it expects all `source` fields to already be resolved to `data:` URLs. An `http://` source in `contents.source` will be ignored/fail silently at apply time.\n\n## The Correct Approach: Inline via `data:` URL\n\nYou must embed the file content directly. Generate the `data:` URL from your config file:\n\n```bash\n# Fetch and encode your config\nprintf 'data:,%s' \"$(curl -s http://internal-server.example.com/configs/myapp.yaml | python3 -c 'import sys,urllib.parse; print(urllib.parse.quote(sys.stdin.read(), safe=\"\"))')\"\n```\n\nThen use it in your MachineConfig:\n\n```yaml\napiVersion: machineconfiguration.openshift.io/v1\nkind: MachineConfig\nmetadata:\n  name: 99-myapp-config\n  labels:\n    machineconfiguration.openshift.io/role: worker  # or: master\nspec:\n  config:\n    ignition:\n      version: 3.4.0\n    storage:\n      files:\n      - path: /etc/myapp/config.yaml\n        mode: 0644\n        overwrite: true\n        contents:\n          source: data:,key%3A%20value%0Aanother%3A%20setting%0A\n```\n\nReplace the `source` value with the output of the command above.\n\n## Why \"Dynamic at Boot\" Doesn't Work Here\n\nMCO's rendering pipeline (`pkg/controller/render/render.go`) intentionally flattens all MachineConfigs into a single rendered config before distribution. Every node gets the **same static snapshot**. If you need nodes to pick up config changes dynamically, the correct workflow is:\n\n1. Update the content in your MachineConfig's `data:` source\n2. Apply the updated MachineConfig to the cluster\n3. MCO rolls out the update node-by-node via its standard drain/apply/reboot cycle\n\nThis is by design \u2014 it gives MCO the ability to track, diff, and safely roll out configuration changes across the cluster."}], "stop_reason": null, "stop_sequence": null, "stop_details": null, "usage": {"input_tokens": 3, "cache_creation_input_tokens": 2505, "cache_read_input_tokens": 33951, "cache_creation": {"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens": 2505, "ephemeral_1h_input_tokens": 0}, "output_tokens": 7}, "context_management": null}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "97616e95-6991-412d-aaaf-43b45e95d486", "uuid": "98cdbb07-30a2-4f8f-bebc-9dd2994ceee7", "request_id": "req_vrtx_011CcK1vhCiGhBDJ2u2xjN7T", "timestamp": "2026-06-22T21:35:15.088Z"}
